    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ee528295-d2bf-45ce-96f9-fece34376c83",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 31-year-old woman with a slender build, standing 5'5\" and weighing approximately 58 kg. She has dark brown hair often pulled back in a bun, and her eyes are sensitive to light even on overcast days. During consultations, she frequently squints under the fluorescent lighting of the clinic and keeps her voice low, as loud sounds seem to exacerbate her discomfort. She appears fatigued, with subtle dark circles beneath her eyes, consistent with disrupted sleep from recurring headache episodes.\n\n{patientName} works as a graphic designer at a mid-sized marketing agency, spending 8–10 hours a day in front of dual computer monitors. The visually intense environment — including screen glare, tight deadlines, and high-pressure project cycles — serves as a significant trigger for her migraines. She often skips meals during crunch periods and drinks 3–4 cups of coffee daily, then struggles to maintain consistent hydration.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys yoga, watercolor painting, and hiking on weekends with her partner. She lives in a busy urban apartment and finds city noise and strong scents (perfumes, cleaning products) particularly bothersome. She describes her social life as active but admits she frequently cancels plans due to migraine attacks, which has caused noticeable stress in her relationships.\n\nHer migraines typically begin with a visual aura — zigzag lines and blind spots lasting 20–30 minutes — followed by a unilateral, pulsating headache of severe intensity, often accompanied by nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia. Attacks last between 12 and 48 hours and occur approximately 3–5 times per month. She rates her peak pain at 8–9/10 on the numeric pain scale.\n\n{patientName} is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally (1–2 glasses of wine on weekends), noting that red wine can sometimes trigger an attack. She is generally health-conscious, follows a mostly plant-based diet, and exercises 3 times per week when her condition allows. She lives with her long-term partner and has a supportive but worried family nearby."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:fbc1d0f9-b4b0-4463-a0e1-260c7041a36e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} first experienced migraines at age 16, initially attributed to academic stress and hormonal changes during puberty. The attacks were infrequent throughout her teenage years but progressively increased in frequency during university, where irregular sleep and caffeine dependence became habitual. She was formally diagnosed with migraine with aura at age 23 by a neurologist after presenting to an emergency department with a prolonged visual disturbance misinterpreted as a TIA.\n\nShe has no history of significant head trauma, hypertension, or seizure disorders. She has no prior hospitalizations beyond the ED visit at age 23. {patientName} has tried several acute and preventive therapies over the years with variable success. She currently manages acute attacks with triptans and OTC analgesics. She reports that her migraines worsen perimenstrually, suggesting a menstrual migraine component.\n\n{patientName} has a documented history of mild anxiety disorder managed with lifestyle interventions (mindfulness, therapy) and no current psychiatric medications. She uses an oral contraceptive pill, which was carefully selected by her gynecologist given the migraine-with-aura history (low-estrogen formulation, with ongoing monitoring). She has no known cardiovascular risk factors and maintains a normal BMI. She is up to date on routine health screenings. No prior surgical history."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
